      "role": "user",
      "content": "Those points are definitely stronger and much more useful for the students. To round out their case, I want them to be prepared to defend the moral or ethical dimensions of the argument.\n\nOften, the opposition tries to frame strict enforcement as inherently inhumane or lacking empathy. How can a debater respond to that in a way that makes a compelling ethical case for strict border control? I'm looking for a sophisticated philosophical or moral defense that moves beyond just \"following the law.\"",
